<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,799,824]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Comments.</emphasis>
This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KITS &amp; MARSHALL" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName=": Comb. Richards" baseAuthorityYear="2013" box="[693,806,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Antrops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setosus">
<emphasis box="[693,806,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. setosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KITS &amp; MARSHALL" authorityYear="2013" box="[862,1041,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Antrops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurantifemur">
<emphasis box="[862,1041,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. aurantifemur</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated based on the black fore femur and the pattern of microtomentum on the pleural sclerites. The species name is derived from the nearest town to the 
<typeStatus box="[372,420,872,896]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
locality; although the road from Quito to Baeza has been fairly well-collected, only a few specimens of this species are known. The name should be treated as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
